    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Tell the Truth About Altered Food; Profits, Not Health</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lewis Chapp letter, commenting on June 4 article, says it is highly doubtful that food companies will responsibly handle food-altering technology without effective government regulation</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I have little faith that private food companies will responsibly handle food-altering technology (''Modified Foods Put Companies in a Quandary,'' front page, June 4). Their goal is profit, not public health.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I have little faith that private food companies will responsibly handle food-altering technology (''Modified Foods Put Companies in a Quandary,'' front page, June 4). Their goal is profit, not public health.</p>
        <p>Without effective government regulations that include criminal penalties when violations of public health are committed, private companies will often elevate profits and stockholders' needs over the general public's.</p>
        <p>If there is a problem of public safety, history shows that most companies treat it as a public relations matter solved by a TV advertising blitz.</p>
        <p>LEWIS CHAPP  Bridgewater, N.J., June 4, 2000</p>
      </block>
